B>   >Greg and John,
B>   >
B>   >I found that by reducing the volume per trade and increasing daily number 
B>of trades ( keeping the 
B>   >total volume per day constant), we can be more profitable.  This is 
B>partially because in a trending market
B>   >we lose less money by following the market more closely. For example, 
B>suppose market move from
B>   >$30 to $35. If per trade volume is 10,000 BBL and the half bid-offer 
B>spread is $1 for simplicity, we take 5
B>   > trades of short positions, the total MTM for that day is 
B>(-5-4-3-2-1)*10,000=-$150,000 and total trading 
B>   >volume is 50,000 BBL short.  If per trade volume is 50,000 BBL, we take 
B>one trade, the total MTM is 
B>   >-5*50,000= -$250,000.   Thus the net difference between the two trading 
B>strategies is $10,000 for that
B>   >particular day.
B>   >
B>   >Therefore it seems that by reducing per trade volume and increasing the 
B>number of trades, we can be more
B>   >profitable as a market maker.  
